{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3cc6673b-ec96-4247-b151-36f137066480","content":"In .NET MAUI, lifecycle management moved from `Application` to `Window`. Override `CreateWindow` in your `App` class and use a custom `Window` subclass:\n\n```csharp\n// App.cs\npublic partial class App : Application\n{\n    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n        => new MyWindow(new AppShell());\n}\n\n// MyWindow.cs\npublic class MyWindow : Window\n{\n    public MyWindow(Page page) : base(page) { }\n\n    protected override void OnCreated()    // ~ OnStart\n    { base.OnCreated(); }\n\n    protected override void OnDeactivated() // ~ OnSleep\n    { base.OnDeactivated(); }\n\n    protected override void OnResumed()     // ~ OnResume\n    { base.OnResumed(); }\n}\n```\n\n**Mapping summary:**\n\n| Xamarin.Forms | MAUI `Window` override |\n|---|---|\n| `OnStart()` | `OnCreated()` / `OnActivated()` |\n| `OnSleep()` | `OnDeactivated()` / `OnStopped()` |\n| `OnResume()` | `OnResumed()` |\n\n`OnActivated`/`OnDeactivated` fire on focus changes; `OnCreated`/`OnStopped` fire on full start/stop — pick whichever matches your original intent.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"6f0b09c4-f55a-478b-803e-70f9d95a17a3","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating lifecycle methods from Xamarin.Forms to .NET MAUI. This is a knowledge question I can answer directly without needing to search the codebase.\n\nIn Xamarin.Forms, you'd override `OnStart()`, `OnSleep()`, and `OnResume()` on the `Application` class.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, the lifecycle model changed. Instead of those overrides, you use the `Window` lifecycle events or the cross-platform lifecycle events via `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` in `MauiProgram.cs`, or you can hook into `Window` events.\n\n\nThe most direct approach is to create a custom `Window` subclass and override its lifecycle methods like `OnCreated()`, `OnActivated()`, `OnDeactivated()`, `OnStopped()`, `OnResumed()`, and `OnDestroying()`, then return it from `Application.CreateWindow()`. Alternatively, you can subscribe directly to events on the `Window` object.","outputTokens":642,"requestId":"77E6:1ECF:711BC5:85CBAF:69EABE91"},"id":"d13d8c9a-485f-4945-9fb7-74dd326c6e15","timestamp":"2026-04-24T00:51:42.716Z","parentId":"837d92e3-dad7-4557-8e44-d8988090633f"}
